    <div class="home-masthead">
      <h1>Jon Sarkin</h1>
      <div class="home-subtitle">1953 &ndash; 2024</div>
    </div>

    <!-- PORTRAIT + INTRO -->
    <div class="intro-row">
      <div class="portrait-area">
        <img alt="Portrait of Jon Sarkin" src="https://catalog.jonsarkin.com/files/original/97396fa496fb7210b0d0b29f6e213f32e05bca3a.jpg" />
        <div class="ph-note">Photo: Janet Knott, Boston Globe</div>
      </div>

      <div class="intro-text">
        <p>In October 1988, Jon Sarkin was a chiropractor in South Hamilton, Massachusetts, when a neurosurgical complication destroyed a significant portion of his left cerebellum. He emerged deaf in one ear, his vision permanently doubled, his balance irreparably altered &mdash; and consumed by an overwhelming, involuntary compulsion to make art.</p>

        <p>For thirty-five years, working from his studio in Gloucester, Massachusetts, Sarkin produced an estimated twenty thousand drawings, paintings, collages, and mixed-media works. His method was stream-of-consciousness: layering ink, marker, paint, and found imagery across paper, foamboard, and disassembled vinyl record sleeves. Recurring motifs &mdash; Batman, cacti, jazz musicians, mantra-like word lists &mdash; cycle through the work with obsessive frequency. He died at his drawing table on July 19, 2024.</p>

        <p>His life and transformation are the subject of <em>Shadows Bright as Glass</em>, by the Pulitzer Prize&ndash;winning journalist Amy Ellis Nutt.</p>
        <a class="bio-link" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jon_Sarkin">Full biography &rarr;</a>
      </div>
    </div>

